## 2. Multi-agent Coordination (state.yml locking)

Concurrent agents can run the lifecycle in parallel. To make corruption-by-concurrency impossible on the shared `state.yml`, `state-machine.py` serializes read-modify-write access with an `fcntl` lock.

### 2.1 Rule catalog

| Rule-id | Origin | Meaning | Exit code |
|---|---|---|---|
| **LCK-001** | `state-machine.py` `_StateLock` | Lock acquire timeout (5s) on `state.yml` — another agent holds the lock | `75` (EX_TEMPFAIL — retryable) |

### 2.2 Lock conventions

`state-machine.py` uses `fcntl.flock` (POSIX-only — framework is Linux-only per operator's env). Two modes:

| Mode | Used by | Semantics |
|---|---|---|
| `LOCK_EX` (exclusive) | `cmd_advance` (read-modify-write writers) | One holder at a time; blocks shared readers |
| `LOCK_SH` (shared) | `cmd_check`, `cmd_state` (read-only) | Multiple shared holders; blocks exclusive writers |

Lock scope = the entire read-modify-write atomic unit (NOT just `save_state`). Locking only `save_state` would leave a race window between `load_state` and `save_state` in `cmd_advance`.

Acquire timeout = **5 seconds**, polled every 50ms. On expiry: `sys.exit(75)` + `LCK-001` to stderr. The exit code matches `sysexits.h` `EX_TEMPFAIL` so callers can distinguish "retry me" from validation failures.

### 2.3 Cross-references

- **ADR-001** FW-004 State Machine — substrate this lock protects.
- **§18 Groundedness Validation** (<TICKET-ID>) — sibling content-correctness layer; same operator-side rule-id pattern.

## 3. Jira Lifecycle Policy: Done-not-Closed

Added by <TICKET-ID> (Phase 4.1). Codifies an operator policy that affects every lifecycle skill: AI-driven workflows terminate Jira tickets at **`Done`**, never at `Closed`.

### 3.1 Policy statement

**Done is the terminal AI-driven state. Closed is operator-only.**

`/update-docs` is the sole skill that transitions a ticket to `Done`, and it does so via Atlassian REST after the merge has landed (the trailing edge of the lifecycle). No skill, hook, or automation transitions a ticket to `Closed`, `Cancelled`, `Won't Do`, or any other non-Done terminal under any condition.

### 3.2 Rationale

- The operator's Jira dashboard needs in-flight visibility of completed-but-uncloseed tickets for retrospective + audit traversal. `Closed` removes the ticket from the active board view.
- Sprint-closure operations (which move many `Done` tickets to `Closed` in one go) are operator-driven, deliberate, and batched — not agent-driven, ad-hoc, per-ticket.
- A `Closed` transition is harder to reverse than a `Done` transition; agents should never make the harder-to-reverse choice on the operator's behalf.

### 3.3 Implementation

`/update-docs` Step 7 (added in this ticket; skill bumped to v2.0.0 X-major per §17):

1. `GET /rest/api/3/issue/<TICKET>/transitions` — discover transition IDs.
2. Find the transition whose `to.name == "Done"`.
3. `POST /rest/api/3/issue/<TICKET>/transitions` with `{"transition": {"id": "<found-id>"}}`.
4. On failure: log to stderr + continue (non-fatal). State-machine `documented` advance still succeeds. Operator transitions manually as fallback.

No other skill transitions Jira beyond `/enrich-us` Step 6 (which moves `To Do` → `Pending refinement validation`, pre-dating §20).

### 3.4 Forbidden transitions

Any transition mapping to a Jira status whose `to.name` is `Closed`, `Cancelled`, `Won't Do`, or any project-specific equivalent that hides the ticket from the active board. If a future skill needs to handle ticket abandonment (e.g., "deviation Scope-Gap re-classified as Won't Fix"), it must surface the decision to the operator, not transition autonomously.

### 3.5 Cross-references

- **ADR-007** Phase 4 entry decisions — documents this policy alongside the multi-agent decisions.
- **`.commands/update-docs.md`** v2.0.0 — the implementation surface.
- **`.commands/enrich-us.md` Step 6** — the only other pattern; pre-dates §20 and is preserved as-is.
- **`integration-state.md`** Changelog narrative — updated each ticket to record the `committed → Done` (Jira) + `documented` (local state machine) terminal pair.

## 4. Pending Improvements Registry

Added by <TICKET-ID> (2026-05-17). Solo-operator pause-friendly safety net: consolidates pending framework improvements into a single source of truth with structured triggers (auto-detectable shell commands + manual `next_check` dates). Companion CLI tool reports eligibility; **never auto-creates Jira tickets** (per `feedback_no_unsolicited_backlog_mining`).

### 4.1 Registry contract

File location: `forge/registers/pending-improvements.yml`.
Schema: `forge/schemas/pending-improvements.schema.yml` (auto-detected by `validate-artifact.py` per the `/registers/pending-improvements\.ya?ml$` rule).
Top-level shape: `{version: "1.0", generated_at: <ISO date>, entries: [...]}`.

Each entry:

```yaml
- id: <kebab-case-slug>          # unique across registry
  source: <attribution>          # audit chapter, follow-up doc, ADR, ticket §X
  status: waiting | eligible | manual-check-due | done | withdrawn
  trigger:
    type: auto | manual
    check: <shell-command-or-description>
    timeout_seconds: <int 1-60>  # auto only; default 10
  last_checked: <ISO date>       # optional
  next_check: <ISO date>         # manual triggers only
  cost_estimate: <free-form>     # e.g. "1h", "1-2 days"
  value_estimate: low | medium | high | critical
  note: <free-form>
  created_at: <ISO date>
```

### 4.2 Trigger types + execution

**`type: auto`** — `check` is a shell command. Tool subprocess-executes with timeout (default 10s, max 60s) and `cwd=framework_root`. Exit 0 = trigger fires → effective status becomes `eligible`. Non-zero exit OR timeout = effective status remains `waiting`. Tool never propagates trigger stderr (failures should be silent; eligibility is the only signal).

**`type: manual`** — `check` is a one-line human-readable description of the activation condition. Tool compares `next_check` date to today: if `next_check ≤ today` → effective status becomes `manual-check-due`. The check field is informational; the date is the gate.

### 4.3 Status lifecycle

```
                         ┌──────────────────────┐
                         │      waiting         │
                         └──────┬───────────────┘
                                │
              auto-trigger fires│       next_check ≤ today
                                │       (manual entries)
                  ┌─────────────┴──────────────┐
                  ▼                            ▼
            ┌──────────┐               ┌──────────────────┐
            │ eligible │               │ manual-check-due │
            └────┬─────┘               └────────┬─────────┘
                 │                              │
                 │   operator decides           │
                 ▼                              ▼
            ┌──────────────────────────────────────┐
            │            done | withdrawn          │
            └──────────────────────────────────────┘
```

Operator transitions to `done` when the improvement is shipped (typically as a Jira ticket merging to main). Operator transitions to `withdrawn` when re-evaluation concludes the improvement won't be pursued. Both are terminal; entries are not deleted (preserve history).

The CLI tool **computes** `eligible`/`manual-check-due` dynamically from triggers — it does not persist these transitions unless the operator runs `--update-checked`. This means a registry entry can show `waiting` in YAML but report `eligible` in the live scan; the YAML is the operator-curated layer.

### 4.4 Operator workflow

**When to ADD an entry**:

- During `/update-docs` Part 5 deviation classification, any deviation classified as `Deferred` or any Recommended Follow-up (record §11) becomes a registry candidate. Operator manually appends an entry. (Auto-coupling /update-docs → registry is a future enhancement; today it's manual.)
- When opening a ticket whose scope explicitly defers something, the deferred item becomes a registry entry.
- When the operator reviews ADRs/audits and identifies a UNASSIGNED item worth observing, an entry is added.

**When to RUN the check**:

- Invoking `/check-pending` skill in Claude Code (preferred).
- Direct CLI: `python3 forge/tools/check-pending-improvements.py --report`.
- Cron (optional, operator-installed): e.g. `0 9 * * 1 cd <framework> && python3 forge/tools/check-pending-improvements.py --eligible-only > /tmp/pending.log 2>&1` (Mondays at 09:00).
- Pre-merge of any framework ticket (informally — before /verify, run --report to ensure no NEW eligibility triggered by your changes).

**When to UPDATE `last_checked`**:

- After reviewing an eligible/manual-check-due item without acting on it: `python3 forge/tools/check-pending-improvements.py --update-checked <id> --note "reviewed at /verify; defer 30 more days"`.
- After acting on it (typically when the item ships as a Jira ticket): operator manually edits `status: done` + `last_checked: <today>` in the YAML (this transition is permanent enough to warrant manual curation).

